If the law is passed, it will be made illegal for Albanian women to travel from the country to receive an abortion—it hard to imagine how a government is going to police this in practice. The law creates the punishment of “civic responsibility”, which means that a fine will be levied on women found carrying materials related to an abortion. This sentence is extended to the man for whom the woman is pregnant.

Abortion is currently a criminal offense in Albania, carried out by punishment of up to four years in prison, and there is no exception in the case of rape. Falasferu's law, although it would legalize abortion in this one scenario, would be a highly restrictive measure as one of the only viable women's health measures in the country.

Women protesters attack police during a demonstration against the family planning law on October 5th 2016, in Tirana, Albania.

Despite the heated public discussion, according to a poll taken by the European Institute for Gender Equality on a small sample of women in October’s Upper House elections, only 19% declared that they planned to vote on the basis of gender issues while 81% made their decision based on party.
